{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17569406","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17569406"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T00:27:20+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T00:27:20+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"22115"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"22115","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/22115"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.08,0.08,0.42,0.39,0.04]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"15076"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"106708"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"15076","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/15076"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"22115"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"89188"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"34"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"656"},{"type":"tags","id":"5826"},{"type":"tags","id":"6000"},{"type":"tags","id":"6523"},{"type":"tags","id":"9600"},{"type":"tags","id":"12913"},{"type":"tags","id":"12919"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"39440"},{"type":"contributions","id":"39441"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"106708","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/106708"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 28-year-old man presents to the Emergency Department after a motorbike accident. He reports severe pain in his right lower leg, which he is unable to move. The injury occurred one hour ago. He has no significant medical history and does not take any regular medications. He works as a mechanic and does not smoke. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears distressed. His pulse rate is 110/min, blood pressure 130/80 mmHg, respiratory rate 18/min, SpO2 99% on room air, and temperature 36.9b0C. There is a 6 cm wound over the anterior aspect of the right tibia with exposed bone and active bleeding. The foot is cool but pulses are palpable. Sensation is reduced over the dorsum of the foot. X-rays confirm a comminuted midshaft tibial fracture with displacement.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most important initial step in management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Apply a plaster backslab","Perform wound closure in the Emergency Department","Administer intravenous antibiotics","Arrange immediate operative fixation","Obtain a computed tomography angiogram"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAdminister intravenous antibiotics\u003C/strong\u003E is the most important initial step in the management of an open fracture. Early administration of broad-spectrum antibiotics significantly reduces the risk of deep infection, which is a major complication of open fractures. Antibiotic prophylaxis should be given as soon as possible for most open fractures (some exceptions include facial fractures not requiring surgical management, isolated distal phalanx of a finger promptly treated within 8 hours), ideally within one hour of presentation, and before surgical intervention.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EApply a plaster backslab\u003C/strong\u003E is important for immobilisation and pain control, but it should be performed after antibiotics are administered and the wound is covered with a sterile dressing. Immobilisation alone does not address the high risk of infection.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EArrange immediate operative fixation\u003C/strong\u003E is necessary for definitive management, but it is not the first step. Surgery should follow initial resuscitation, antibiotic administration, and assessment for neurovascular compromise.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EObtain a computed tomography angiogram\u003C/strong\u003E may be indicated if there is suspicion of vascular injury, but in this case, pulses are present. The priority remains infection prevention.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPerform wound closure in the Emergency Department\u003C/strong\u003E is not appropriate for open fractures. The wound should be covered with a sterile dressing and left open until formal surgical debridement can be performed in theatre to reduce infection risk.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOpen fractures are orthopaedic emergencies due to the risk of infection, neurovascular injury, and compartment syndrome. Early antibiotics, tetanus prophylaxis, sterile wound coverage, and prompt surgical debridement are key steps in management.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Most open fractures require urgent intravenous antibiotics and surgical debridement to reduce infection risk.","Early assessment for neurovascular compromise is essential in open fractures.","Tetanus prophylaxis should be considered in all open fracture cases."],"references":["Whiting PS, Obremskey W, Johal H, Shearer D, Volgas D, Balogh ZJ. Open fractures: evidence-based best practices. OTA Int. 2024 May 3;7(3 Suppl):e313. doi: 10.1097/OI9.0000000000000313. PMID: 38708043; PMCID: PMC11064778. Available from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/38708043/","Sop JL, Sop A. Open Fracture Management. [Updated 2023 Aug 8]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2025 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK448083/","Davies M, Dorrell V, Grainger C, Ahluwalia A, Vasireddy A, Ahluwalia R. Assessing and managing open fractures: a systematic approach. Br J Hosp Med (Lond). 2022 Dec 2;83(12):1-9. doi: 10.12968/hmed.2021.0578. Epub 2022 Dec 29. PMID: 36594765. Available from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/36594765/","Dheenadhayalan J, Nagashree V, Devendra A, Velmurugesan PS, Rajasekaran S. Management of open fractures: A narrative review. J Clin Orthop Trauma. 2023 Sep 1;44:102246. doi: 10.1016/j.jcot.2023.102246. PMID: 37720489; PMCID: PMC10502353. Available from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/37720489/","Therapeutic Guidelines Limited. Open fractures. In: Therapeutic Guidelines: Antibiotic [Internet]. Version 17. Melbourne: Therapeutic Guidelines Limited; 2025 [cited 2025 Jun 22]. Available from: https://www.tg.org.au/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"89188"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"22115"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"89188","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/89188"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-06-22T09:42:08+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-06-22T09:43:15+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"15076"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"106708"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"24","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/24"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\ude91","name":"Emergency Medicine","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"5"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"34","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/34"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\uddb4","name":"Orthopaedics","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:47:20+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"2"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"66","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/66"},"attributes":{"emoji